<h2>Class 1 Overview</h2>
<div class="inote"><div class="lbl">📋 Instructor Prep</div>This is the tone-setting class of the semester — everything downstream (stakeholder analysis, scope/WBS, scheduling, cost control) refers back to the charter and PMP built conceptually here. Students routinely treat "charter" and "PMP" as interchangeable; the Charter vs. PMP comparison table and Activity #1 exist specifically to break that habit early. Protect 10–12 minutes for the Activity #1 debrief — that's where the distinction actually clicks. Course runs Aug 25–Dec 3, 2026 (no class Nov 23–27, Thanksgiving break).</div>
<h3>Timed Lecture Outline</h3>
<div class="tl">
<div class="tli"><span class="ttime">0:00–0:08 (8 min)</span><div class="ttitle">Hook &amp; Context</div><div class="tdesc">Real case: a team skipped chartering and went straight to scheduling — disagreement over "success" surfaces at 60% complete, triggering rework and a schedule claim. Why Class 1 is the foundation every other class builds on.</div></div>
<div class="tli"><span class="ttime">0:08–0:20 (12 min)</span><div class="ttitle">The Project Life Cycle &amp; Process Groups</div><div class="tdesc">PMBOK's five process groups mapped onto a construction project's phases: pursuit/preconstruction, award, mobilization, construction, closeout.</div></div>
<div class="tli"><span class="ttime">0:20–0:35 (15 min)</span><div class="ttitle">Project Initiation &amp; the Project Charter</div><div class="tdesc">Required charter elements, PM authority thresholds, the KSU case example, charter authority table.</div></div>
<div class="tli"><span class="ttime">0:35–0:50 (15 min)</span><div class="ttitle">Project Setup Essentials</div><div class="tdesc">Team mobilization, kickoff meeting agenda, document control systems, communication protocols.</div></div>
<div class="tli"><span class="ttime">0:50–1:00 (10 min)</span><div class="ttitle">Activity #1: "Charter or PMP?" Debrief</div><div class="tdesc">Small groups sort 8 real statements. Debrief as a class — spend the most time on items 4 and 5, which are deliberately ambiguous.</div></div>
<div class="tli"><span class="ttime">1:00–1:09 (9 min)</span><div class="ttitle">The Project Management Plan (PMP)</div><div class="tdesc">Subsidiary plans overview, charter-vs-PMP comparison, why the PMP is a living document rather than a signed-once authorization.</div></div>
<div class="tli"><span class="ttime">1:09–1:15 (6 min)</span><div class="ttitle">Ethics &amp; Leadership: Integrity in Chartering</div><div class="tdesc">PMI Code of Ethics and Professional Conduct applied to honest success-criteria setting and authority boundaries. Wrap-up and homework assignment.</div></div>
</div>
<div class="callout cg"><strong>⚡ Teaching Tip</strong>Students will want to treat the charter as a longer document than it should be. Keep repeating: if it takes more than five minutes to read, it's PMP content, not charter content. That single rule resolves most of the sorting-activity disagreements.</div>
</div>
