<h2>Learning Objectives</h2>
<p>By the end of Class 1, students will be able to:</p>
<ul class="objlist">
<li class="objitem"><span class="objnum">1</span><div>Explain the purpose of project initiation and where it fits within the PMBOK process groups and the construction project life cycle.</div></li>
<li class="objitem"><span class="objnum">2</span><div>Identify the required elements of a project charter and explain why the charter authorizes project start.</div></li>
<li class="objitem"><span class="objnum">3</span><div>Distinguish a project charter from a project management plan (PMP) in purpose, length, audience, and update frequency.</div></li>
<li class="objitem"><span class="objnum">4</span><div>Describe the core subsidiary plans of a construction PMP: scope, schedule, cost, quality, resources, communications, risk, and procurement.</div></li>
<li class="objitem"><span class="objnum">5</span><div>Apply the PMI Code of Ethics and Professional Conduct to a chartering scenario involving pressure to overstate certainty.</div></li>
<li class="objitem"><span class="objnum">6</span><div>Evaluate how weak project setup decisions propagate into downstream cost, schedule, and risk exposure.</div></li>
</ul>
<div class="inote"><div class="lbl">📋 Bloom's Alignment</div>Objectives 1–3: Remember/Understand. Objective 4: Apply. Objective 5: Evaluate (ethics reasoning). Objective 6: Analyze/Evaluate. Push hardest on Objectives 5–6 during wrap-up — they separate a PM who fills out templates from one who understands why the templates exist.</div>
<h3>Career Relevance</h3>
<div class="card">
<h4>Why Every Construction PM Needs This Class</h4>
<ul>
<li><strong>Contract Kickoff:</strong> The charter is often the first internal document a newly-assigned PM produces after contract award — it's a professional credibility marker.</li>
<li><strong>Authority Disputes:</strong> Unclear PM authority thresholds are a leading cause of change-order friction between field staff and ownership.</li>
<li><strong>Onboarding New Team Members:</strong> A clear PMP lets superintendents, project engineers, and subs get oriented fast instead of learning project rules by trial and error.</li>
<li><strong>Claims &amp; Disputes:</strong> When projects end up in dispute, the charter and PMP are often the first documents attorneys request — they establish what "success" was agreed to look like.</li>
</ul>
