<h2>Lecture Notes — Initiation, Setup &amp; the PMP</h2>
<h3>1.1 The Project Life Cycle &amp; Process Groups</h3>
<p>Every project — construction or otherwise — moves through five PMBOK <strong>process groups</strong>: Initiating, Planning, Executing, Monitoring &amp; Controlling, and Closing. Monitoring &amp; Controlling runs concurrently across the others rather than as a discrete phase.</p>
<div class="card">
<h4>Construction-Specific Overlay</h4>
<table>
<thead><tr><th>PMBOK Process Group</th><th>Construction Phase</th></tr></thead>
<tbody>
<tr><td>Initiating</td><td>Contract award, chartering, PM assignment</td></tr>
<tr><td>Planning</td><td>Preconstruction, PMP development, subcontractor buyout</td></tr>
<tr><td>Executing</td><td>Mobilization &amp; construction</td></tr>
<tr><td>Monitoring &amp; Controlling</td><td>Ongoing throughout — cost/schedule tracking, change management, QA/QC</td></tr>
<tr><td>Closing</td><td>Substantial completion, punch list, closeout, final payment</td></tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
<div class="callout cb"><strong>🔑 Key Concept</strong>Initiation is short but consequential — it sets the authority, objectives, and success criteria that every later process group is measured against.</div>
<h3>1.2 Project Initiation &amp; the Project Charter</h3>
<p>A <strong>project charter</strong> is the document that formally authorizes a project's existence and gives the project manager authority to apply organizational resources to project activities.</p>
<div class="card">
<h4>Required Charter Elements</h4>
<ol>
<li><strong>Purpose &amp; business justification</strong> — why this project exists, in 2–3 sentences.</li>
<li><strong>Measurable success criteria</strong> — cost, schedule, and quality targets that can be checked against later.</li>
<li><strong>PM name &amp; authority level</strong> — explicit budget and change-approval thresholds.</li>
<li><strong>Stakeholder list</strong> — high-level, not the detailed analysis that comes later (Class 2).</li>
<li><strong>Summary milestone schedule</strong> — start, key phases, substantial completion.</li>
<li><strong>Summary budget</strong> — GMP or contract value and major cost categories.</li>
<li><strong>High-level risks &amp; assumptions</strong> — site conditions, delivery method, known constraints.</li>
<li><strong>Sponsor &amp; PM signatures</strong> — the act of formal authorization.</li>
</ol>
</div>
<div class="inote"><div class="lbl">📋 Case Example — Use Throughout the Semester</div>KSU Applied Technology &amp; Construction Innovation Center: $28.5M GMP, 72,000 SF, 3 stories, CM at Risk (AIA A133), 16-month duration, occupied urban campus. This recurring case resurfaces in Class 2 (stakeholders), Class 3 (delivery methods &amp; procurement), and later scheduling/cost classes — keep the same numbers so students build cumulative familiarity.</div>
<div class="card">
<h4>Charter Authority Table — Who Decides What</h4>
<div class="ot"><table>
<thead><tr><th>Decision Type</th><th>Typical Authority</th><th>Example Threshold</th></tr></thead>
<tbody>
<tr><td>Minor budget reallocation within GMP</td><td>Project Manager</td><td>Up to $25,000–$50,000 per change</td></tr>
<tr><td>Schedule adjustments not affecting milestones</td><td>Project Manager</td><td>±2 weeks on non-critical activities</td></tr>
<tr><td>Scope changes affecting the GMP</td><td>Owner / Sponsor</td><td>Any change requiring a formal change order</td></tr>
<tr><td>Substantial completion date changes</td><td>Owner / Sponsor</td><td>Any milestone shift</td></tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>
</div>
<h3>1.3 Project Setup Essentials</h3>
<div class="grid2">
<div class="card">
<h4>Team Mobilization</h4>
<p>Core CM at Risk field team typically includes: Project Manager, Superintendent, Project Engineer(s), Estimator/Buyout Lead, Safety Manager, and Document Control Coordinator on larger projects.</p>
</div>
<div class="card">
<h4>Kickoff Meeting Agenda</h4>
<ul>
<li>Introductions &amp; roles</li>
<li>Charter review &amp; success criteria</li>
<li>Contract/GMP review</li>
<li>Milestone schedule overview</li>
<li>Communication protocols &amp; submittal process</li>
<li>Site logistics &amp; safety orientation</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
<div class="card">
<h4>Document Control Systems</h4>
<p>Set up before mobilization, not after the first RFI arrives: submittal log, RFI log, change order log, meeting minutes numbering convention, and a shared drawing/document repository with version control.</p>
</div>
<div class="callout cr"><strong>⚠ Common Setup Failure</strong>Teams that delay document control setup until "things settle down" lose the ability to reconstruct decision history when disputes arise later — by then it's too late to retrofit a numbering convention onto three months of untracked emails.</div>
<h3>1.4 The Project Management Plan (PMP)</h3>
<p>The <strong>project management plan (PMP)</strong> describes how the project will be executed, monitored, controlled, and closed. It aggregates subsidiary management plans developed during the Planning process group.</p>
<div class="ot"><table>
<thead><tr><th>Subsidiary Plan</th><th>Construction Focus</th></tr></thead>
<tbody>
<tr><td>Scope Management Plan</td><td>WBS, scope statement, change control process</td></tr>
<tr><td>Schedule Management Plan</td><td>CPM schedule, update frequency, float policy</td></tr>
<tr><td>Cost Management Plan</td><td>Budget tracking, cost codes, forecasting method</td></tr>
<tr><td>Quality Management Plan</td><td>QA/QC procedures, inspection &amp; test plans</td></tr>
<tr><td>Resource Management Plan</td><td>Staffing plan, subcontractor management</td></tr>
<tr><td>Communications Management Plan</td><td>Meeting cadence, reporting formats, escalation paths</td></tr>
<tr><td>Risk Management Plan</td><td>Risk register, response strategies, contingency</td></tr>
<tr><td>Procurement Management Plan</td><td>Subcontractor buyout strategy, bid packages</td></tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>
<h3>1.5 Charter vs. PMP — Quick Comparison</h3>
<div class="ot"><table>
<thead><tr><th>Feature</th><th>Project Charter</th><th>Project Management Plan</th></tr></thead>
<tbody>
<tr><td>Purpose</td><td>Authorizes the project</td><td>Operationalizes the project</td></tr>
<tr><td>Length</td><td>1–2 pages</td><td>Dozens of pages across subsidiary plans</td></tr>
<tr><td>Audience</td><td>Sponsor, executives, PM</td><td>Full project team</td></tr>
<tr><td>Timing</td><td>Signed once, at initiation</td><td>Developed in planning, refined throughout</td></tr>
<tr><td>Update frequency</td><td>Rarely amended</td><td>Living document, updated as needed</td></tr>
<tr><td>Authority</td><td>Grants PM authority</td><td>Describes how that authority is exercised</td></tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>
<div class="inote"><div class="lbl">📋 Talking Point</div>"The charter is a promise; the PMP is the plan for keeping it." Ask students: if the charter says substantial completion by April 2028, which subsidiary plan is responsible for actually protecting that date? (Schedule Management Plan — ties directly into Class 8's CPM work.)</div>
</div>
</div>
