<h2>Key Terms — Class 1</h2>
<div class="inote"><div class="lbl">📋 Note</div>Student edition has definitions blank for note-taking. These are the complete definitions for your reference.</div>
<div class="grid2">
<div class="card"><h4>Project Charter</h4><p>The document that formally authorizes a project's existence and gives the project manager authority to apply organizational resources to project activities.</p></div><div class="card"><h4>Project Management Plan (PMP)</h4><p>The document that describes how a project will be executed, monitored, controlled, and closed; aggregates all subsidiary management plans.</p></div><div class="card"><h4>Project Life Cycle</h4><p>The series of phases a project passes through from initiation to closure.</p></div><div class="card"><h4>Process Groups</h4><p>The five PMBOK categories of project management activity: Initiating, Planning, Executing, Monitoring &amp; Controlling, Closing.</p></div><div class="card"><h4>Sponsor</h4><p>The individual or group providing resources and support for the project and accountable for enabling success — typically the owner's representative.</p></div><div class="card"><h4>GMP (Guaranteed Maximum Price)</h4><p>The maximum price a CM at Risk contractor guarantees for a defined scope; savings below GMP are typically shared per the contract.</p></div><div class="card"><h4>CM at Risk</h4><p>A delivery method where the construction manager holds the risk of delivering the project within the GMP, acting as general contractor during construction.</p></div><div class="card"><h4>Kickoff Meeting</h4><p>The first formal meeting between owner, design team, and CM to align on charter contents, communication protocols, and logistics.</p></div><div class="card"><h4>Document Control</h4><p>The system of logs, numbering conventions, and repositories used to track submittals, RFIs, change orders, and correspondence.</p></div><div class="card"><h4>Baseline</h4><p>The approved version of a plan (scope, schedule, or cost) used as a basis for comparison against actual performance.</p></div><div class="card"><h4>Subsidiary Plan</h4><p>One of the component plans (scope, schedule, cost, quality, resources, communications, risk, procurement) that together make up the PMP.</p></div><div class="card"><h4>PM Authority Threshold</h4><p>The explicit dollar or decision-scope limit within which a project manager may act without escalating to the sponsor or owner.</p></div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
