<h2>In-Class Activities</h2>
<div class="actbox">
<h3>Activity #1 — "Charter or PMP?" Sorting Challenge</h3>
<div class="actmeta">
<div class="amitem">Format: <span>Small groups (3–4 students)</span></div>
<div class="amitem">Time: <span>12 minutes + debrief</span></div>
<div class="amitem">Ordered: <span>Straightforward → Debatable</span></div>
</div>
<p>Groups sort each statement into Charter, PMP, Both, or Neither, then justify their choice.</p>
</div>
<div class="inote"><div class="lbl">📋 Debrief Guide</div>Project statements one at a time; allow 30–45 seconds of group discussion before revealing the answer. Items 1–3 are straightforward; items 4–5 are deliberately ambiguous and deserve the most debrief time — they show that the charter's stakeholder list is high-level while the PMP's is detailed, and that document-control conventions belong to the Communications Management Plan even though they feel administrative.</div>
<div class="grid2">
<div class="qq"><div class="qnum">Item 1</div><div class="qtext">"Project success will be measured by substantial completion by April 2028 and final cost at or below the $28.5M GMP."</div><div class="ans"><strong>Charter.</strong> Measurable success criteria belong in the charter.</div></div>
<div class="qq"><div class="qnum">Item 2</div><div class="qtext">"Detailed CPM schedule with 400 activities and logic ties."</div><div class="ans"><strong>PMP.</strong> Schedule Management Plan detail — far beyond charter scope.</div></div>
<div class="qq"><div class="qnum">Item 3</div><div class="qtext">"PM Sarah Chen has authority to approve change orders up to $50,000 without Board approval."</div><div class="ans"><strong>Charter.</strong> PM authority threshold is core charter content.</div></div>
<div class="qq"><div class="qnum">Item 4</div><div class="qtext">"Submittal log format, numbering convention, and 10-day owner review turnaround."</div><div class="ans"><strong>PMP.</strong> Communications Management Plan / document control — administrative detail belongs downstream of the charter.</div></div>
<div class="qq"><div class="qnum">Item 5</div><div class="qtext">"List of all identified stakeholders and their level of influence."</div><div class="ans"><strong>Both.</strong> The charter includes a high-level stakeholder list; the detailed influence analysis is a PMP/Stakeholder Engagement Plan artifact (preview of Class 2).</div></div>
<div class="qq"><div class="qnum">Item 6</div><div class="qtext">"One paragraph explaining why KSU is building this facility."</div><div class="ans"><strong>Charter.</strong> Purpose and business justification.</div></div>
<div class="qq"><div class="qnum">Item 7</div><div class="qtext">"Weekly OAC meeting schedule and agenda template."</div><div class="ans"><strong>PMP.</strong> Communications Management Plan.</div></div>
<div class="qq"><div class="qnum">Item 8</div><div class="qtext">"Signature blocks for the owner's VP of Facilities and the CM's project executive."</div><div class="ans"><strong>Charter.</strong> The signatures are the act of formal authorization.</div></div>
</div>
<div class="actbox" style="margin-top:32px;">
<h3>Activity #2 — "Draft Your Kickoff Agenda"</h3>
<div class="actmeta">
<div class="amitem">Format: <span>Pairs</span></div>
<div class="amitem">Time: <span>8 minutes + 4 min debrief</span></div>
</div>
<p>Using the KSU case, draft a 6-item kickoff meeting agenda for the first OAC (owner-architect-contractor) meeting.</p>
</div>
<div class="card">
<h4>Scenario</h4>
<p>Dr. Patricia Moore, KSU's Director of Capital Projects, has asked you to run the kickoff meeting Thursday morning. She wants the design team, your superintendent, and the estimator all aligned before anyone touches a shovel.</p>
<ol>
<li>What six items belong on the agenda, and in what order?</li>
<li>Why does that order matter?</li>
</ol>
</div>
<div class="ans"><strong>Answer Key:</strong><br/>
<strong>1.</strong> Introductions &amp; roles → Review of charter &amp; success criteria → Contract/GMP review → Milestone schedule overview → Communication protocols &amp; submittal process → Site logistics, safety orientation &amp; next steps.<br/><br/>
<strong>2.</strong> The agenda should move from alignment (who's here, what we agreed to) to operational detail (how we'll actually run the job) — not the reverse. Starting with logistics before the team agrees on the charter's success criteria risks solving the wrong problems well.
</div>
</div>
</div>
