<h2>Ethics, Leadership &amp; Professional Decision-Making</h2>
<p>Chartering is where a construction PM's professional judgment is tested first — before any concrete is poured, the words written into the charter set expectations that real money and real trust will later be measured against.</p>
<h3>The PMI Code of Ethics and Professional Conduct</h3>
<div class="grid2">
<div class="card"><h4>Responsibility</h4><p>Owning the accuracy of the success criteria and authority thresholds you write into the charter — not overpromising to please a sponsor eager for good news.</p></div>
<div class="card"><h4>Respect</h4><p>Treating every team member's setup input — superintendent, estimator, safety manager — as legitimate, even when it slows down a fast kickoff timeline.</p></div>
<div class="card"><h4>Fairness</h4><p>Making sure the charter's authority thresholds and stakeholder list aren't quietly shaped to benefit one party's convenience over the project's actual needs.</p></div>
<div class="card"><h4>Honesty</h4><p>Communicating real risks and assumptions in the charter — not softening them to make a project look more certain than it is.</p></div>
</div>
<div class="callout cb"><strong>🔑 Source</strong>Project Management Institute, <em>Code of Ethics and Professional Conduct</em>. These four values apply directly to chartering: a PM who signs off on a completion date they privately doubt violates Honesty even if the sponsor requested it.</div>
<h3>Scenario: "The Optimistic Charter"</h3>
<div class="card">
<p>Dr. Patricia Moore wants the charter to state substantial completion by <strong>February 2028</strong> — two months earlier than your own schedule assessment supports — because the earlier date "will look better to the Board of Regents." She's not asking you to lie about the GMP or scope, just to write down a more aggressive date than you believe is achievable.</p>
<ol>
<li>Is it dishonest to write a date you privately doubt, if the owner directed it?</li>
<li>How does an inflated charter set the whole project up for conflict later?</li>
<li>What is the PM's professional obligation when asked to write something they believe is misleading?</li>
</ol>
</div>
<div class="inote"><div class="lbl">📋 Discussion Guide</div>Q1: Push past "I was just following instructions" — PMI's Honesty value obligates the PM to communicate the truth as they understand it, not just transcribe what's requested. Q2: Look for answers connecting an unrealistic charter date to later schedule disputes, forced acceleration costs, or a credibility hit when the date inevitably slips. Q3: The professional answer is to state the concern directly and in writing (e.g., "I can include February 2028 if you'd like, but my assessment supports April 2028 based on X, Y, Z"), giving the sponsor an informed choice rather than silently complying or silently refusing.</div>
<h3>Leading Through Setup Ambiguity</h3>
<p>Early in a project, almost nothing is settled — the team is new, the document conventions don't exist yet, and everyone is watching how the PM handles the first few ambiguous decisions. A PM who models document discipline and honest communication in Week 1 sets the team's norms for the next sixteen months; a PM who cuts corners at kickoff normalizes cutting corners later.</p>
<h3>A Simple Professional Decision-Making Framework</h3>
<div class="card">
<h4>Four Steps</h4>
<ol>
<li><strong>Identify the issue</strong> — name the conflict or dilemma precisely, not vaguely</li>
<li><strong>Consider stakeholders and PMI's four values</strong> — who is affected, and which value is most at stake?</li>
<li><strong>Evaluate alternatives</strong> — what are the realistic options, including disclosure and pushback?</li>
<li><strong>Act and document</strong> — take the action and create a contemporaneous record of why</li>
</ol>
</div>
<h3>Discussion Questions</h3>
<ol>
<li>Where is the line between "confident leadership" and "overpromising" when writing charter success criteria?</li>
<li>How would you document your schedule concern in writing so it protects both you and the owner later?</li>
<li>If Dr. Moore insisted on the February date anyway, what would you do next?</li>
</ol>
<div class="inote"><div class="lbl">📋 Discussion Guide</div>Q1: Confident leadership commits to criteria the PM has actually assessed as achievable; overpromising commits to criteria chosen for how they sound. Q2: Look for answers mentioning a dated email or meeting minute stating the assessment and the recommendation, distinct from simply complying. Q3: Acceptable answers include escalating the concern once more in writing, offering a contingency-based alternative (e.g., "achievable if X happens by Y date"), or ultimately complying while preserving a paper trail — not simply capitulating without documentation.</div>
</div>
</div>
