<div class="inote"><div class="lbl">📋 Grading Note</div>Problems 1–2: recall + application. Problem 3: high-value scenario requiring synthesis across the charter/PMP distinction. Problem 4: professional reflection building judgment. Full answer keys included below each problem.</div>
<div class="hwp">
<div class="hwnum">Problem 1 — Charter Element Matching (15 pts, 3 pts each)</div>
<p>Match each description to the correct charter element: Purpose/Justification, Success Criteria, Authority Level, Milestone Summary, Stakeholder List.</p>
<ol type="a">
<li>"Substantial completion is targeted for April 2028."</li>
<li>"KSU is building this facility to consolidate three outdated labs into one accredited teaching space."</li>
<li>"The PM may approve change orders up to $50,000 without Board sign-off."</li>
<li>"Dr. Patricia Moore (KSU), the design architect, and the CM's project executive are named participants."</li>
<li>"Final cost must not exceed the $28.5M GMP."</li>
</ol>
<div class="ans"><strong>Answer Key:</strong><br/>
a. Milestone Summary. b. Purpose/Justification. c. Authority Level. d. Stakeholder List. e. Success Criteria.</div>
</div>
<div class="hwp">
<div class="hwnum">Problem 2 — True/False with Justification (10 pts, 2 pts each)</div>
<ol type="a">
<li>The project charter and the PMP are updated on the same schedule throughout the project.</li>
<li>A project charter should be short enough to read in about five minutes.</li>
<li>The Schedule Management Plan is part of the project charter, not the PMP.</li>
<li>Document control systems should be set up before mobilization begins.</li>
<li>The charter's stakeholder list is expected to be as detailed as the PMP's stakeholder engagement plan.</li>
</ol>
<div class="ans"><strong>Answer Key:</strong><br/>
a. <strong>FALSE</strong> — the charter is signed once at initiation; the PMP is a living document updated throughout planning and execution.<br/>
b. <strong>TRUE</strong> — 1–2 pages, readable in minutes; anything longer is PMP content.<br/>
c. <strong>FALSE</strong> — the detailed CPM schedule lives in the Schedule Management Plan within the PMP.<br/>
d. <strong>TRUE</strong> — setting up logs and conventions after work starts means losing the ability to reconstruct early decisions.<br/>
e. <strong>FALSE</strong> — the charter list is high-level; detailed influence/interest analysis is a PMP/stakeholder engagement artifact (Class 2 topic).</div>
</div>
<div class="hwp">
<div class="hwnum">Problem 3 — Case Study (20 pts)</div>
<p>You are the newly-assigned PM for a $12M student housing renovation project (200 beds, occupied-during-construction phasing, 10-month duration, CM at Risk). Draft:</p>
<ol type="a">
<li>Three measurable success criteria for the project charter.</li>
<li>A one-sentence PM authority statement with a specific dollar threshold.</li>
<li>The three subsidiary PMP plans you consider most critical for this project, with one sentence justifying each.</li>
</ol>
<div class="ans"><strong>Answer Key (sample — accept reasonable variation):</strong><br/>
a. Substantial completion within 10 months; final cost at or below $12M GMP; zero life-safety incidents affecting occupied residents during construction.<br/>
b. "The PM may approve change orders up to $30,000 per occurrence without owner Board approval."<br/>
c. <em>Risk Management Plan</em> — occupied-during-construction phasing creates elevated life-safety and disruption risk. <em>Communications Management Plan</em> — resident notification and coordination is critical given active occupancy. <em>Schedule Management Plan</em> — phased/sequenced work around occupied units requires tight logic and float management. Credit any three well-justified plans tied to the case's actual constraints.</div>
</div>
<div class="hwp">
<div class="hwnum">Problem 4 — Professional Reflection (5 pts)</div>
<p>In 150–200 words, describe a real or plausible scenario where a project started without a clear charter or PMP, and problems surfaced downstream. What went wrong? What were the consequences? How could a PM have caught it earlier?</p>
<div class="ans"><strong>Answer Key:</strong><br/>
<strong>Grading Rubric:</strong> Clear scenario (1 pt) + correct identification of the charter/PMP gap (1 pt) + specific consequences discussed (1 pt) + practical PM lesson drawn (1 pt) + professional writing quality (1 pt). Accept any plausible scenario. Look for evidence the student understands that initiation decisions have real downstream budget/schedule consequences, and that a PM can catch these early.</div>
</div>
