<div class="chki"><div class="chkb"></div><div><strong>Step 1:</strong> Confirm delivery method and contract terms (GMP, milestones, key exhibits) before drafting anything.</div></div>
<div class="chki"><div class="chkb"></div><div><strong>Step 2:</strong> Draft the charter with the owner/sponsor — confirm purpose, success criteria, and authority thresholds together, not in isolation.</div></div>
<div class="chki"><div class="chkb"></div><div><strong>Step 3:</strong> Define PM authority thresholds explicitly, in dollars, for both budget and schedule decisions.</div></div>
<div class="chki"><div class="chkb"></div><div><strong>Step 4:</strong> Identify high-level stakeholders and confirm the charter's stakeholder list before kickoff.</div></div>
<div class="chki"><div class="chkb"></div><div><strong>Step 5:</strong> Set up document control systems (submittal log, RFI log, change order log, numbering convention) before mobilization.</div></div>
<div class="chki"><div class="chkb"></div><div><strong>Step 6:</strong> Schedule and run the kickoff meeting using an agenda that moves from alignment to operational detail.</div></div>
<div class="chki"><div class="chkb"></div><div><strong>Step 7:</strong> Outline the PMP's subsidiary plans and assign an owner for each (scope, schedule, cost, quality, resources, comms, risk, procurement).</div></div>
<div class="chki"><div class="chkb"></div><div><strong>Step 8:</strong> Obtain formal charter sign-off from sponsor and PM before treating the project as authorized.</div></div>
